      "title": "[Hackaday] Disassembling Opcodes with a Font",
      "content_html": "<img src=\"https://hackaday.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/z80_sans.gif\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n<div><img alt=\"An animation shows an open document in LibreOffice Write. In the document are some hexadecimal opcodes. The operator selects these opcodes and changes their font to Z80 Sans, at which point they are displayed as assembly mnemonic codes.\" class=\"attachment-large size-large wp-post-image\" height=\"533\" src=\"https://hackaday.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/z80_sans.gif?w=800\" style=\"margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 15px;\" width=\"800\" /></div>Those who stay into the forbidden realm of font rendering quickly learn how convoluted and arcane it can be – LaTeX is a fully Turing-complete programming language, Unicode has over <a class=\"read-more\" href=\"https://hackaday.com/2026/03/15/disassembling-opcodes-with-a-font/\">&#8230;read more</a>",
